title: For Sale/Trade:  Federal Auto Match 22LR
location: Beloit Township, a few miles south of, Janesville, Wisconsin
postcontent:
I spent the last 8 months acquiring the AUTO MATCH while shooting my cheaper ammo and was saving it for when the cheaper stuff was all shot. The cheap stuff was recently used up and I just found out that while my Ruger 10/22 semi-auto loves the Auto Match, my Marlin XT-22 bolt actions' don't much care for it.
I would have thought a bolt action .22 would not care what you ran through it, but my Marlins are picky.
If you've got a semi-auto pistol or rifle and want a great cycling and clean burning ammo that does not gum up the action and leave everything covered in a heavy coat of gritty residue, the auto match is great stuff. I'm keeping one case of it for my Ruger.
The other case I would like to trade for 36 grain copper plated Federal Champion. My Marlin bolt action rifles cycle the 36 grain Federal Champion fine and don't care that it's dirtier.
All my Auto Match for trade is new and unopened, and I would like the same of what I trade for. No loose rounds in zip lock bags please. Also, no aguila or Remington Thunderbolts.
As a last resort. I will consider selling the Auto Match outright for $30 per box, then searching for and buying the ammo I want. I would much rather just trade.
So if anyone out there has any of the 36 grain Federal Champion 22LR, and it just doesn't cycle their semi-auto as good as they'd like, make a trade with me.
I'll trade straight up, round for round of Federal Champion. Got something similar? Make me an offer.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 Carbine Project Gun
postcontent:
Up for sale or trade is a universal m1 carbine  with folding stock and 20 rd mag. This is an early Generation 2 universal which basically means that it's got a mix of USGI and Universal specific parts. The gun has two recoil springs. It sits in an under folding wood stock which puts the entire length at 26 1/2" folded. It shoots great and does not jam. This would make a great truck, backpacking, nightstand gun.

Now for the bad. One of the things universal did was stop using the cupped operating rod and went to a cutout to operate the bolt. This is known to be an inherent weakness in the design. Sure enough, this one has a crack. I have shot it with it cracked, but it needs welded, smoothed and reblued to be right. 
The second problem is the pistol grip broke off at some point. It was doweled and glued and has not been an issue since I've owned it, but there is a hairline crack all the way around the grip. It sits on my reloading bench on the grip for the past year or so with zero problem, but it's noticeable. I was debating just cutting the damn thing off flush and putting an AR grip on it, but never got around to it. I think it would be an improvement.



Asking $350 OBO

Willing to trade for working firearms, no Lorcin, Jimenez, Hi Point, etc.

Willing to meet from Lacey to Tacoma/Puyallup and Tenino area. Roy/McKenna/Yelm preferred.

title: For Sale:  Beretta 950 BS Minx 22 Short Semi Automatic Pistol SALE PENDING
postcontent:
This is a post-1968 American made 2’’ 950 BS Minx with the thumb safety. 
It holds six rounds of .22 short in the magazine and one in the chamber.
These small framed, Beretta pistols use a super simple blowback action. 
This also means the gun has a pretty stout recoil spring to keep the 
action pushed forward and a short slide—and this makes it hard for 
some to grip. 
To get around this, Beretta used a barrel with a pivot pin that pops 
up and out of battery when a latch is depressed. 
With the barrel tipped up, you can load, unload, reload, and 
check to see if you have a loaded chamber with the flick of the lever.
The .22 Short models were discontinued after 1992.
If the post is up I still have it.

title: For Sale:  MAUSER MODEL 1910-25 ACP, MADE IN 1920'S BEAUTIFUL!
postcontent:
Up for sale is a gorgeous, all original, pre-war, Mauser Model 1910. This rare example is chambered in 25 acp, whereas most of these were chambered in 32. A antique arms dealer examined it and told me that the low, 5-digit serial number indicates a manufacture date in the 1920's. These fine German pistols are serialized on just about every part...and all numbers match on this gun. This is also an early import gun, that made it to the states before 1968, as it doesn't have the gaudy importer's mark (Importer's name, city and state), but rather simply says "Germany" on the top of the barrel. The blued finish of the gun is in great, original condition, with about 75-80% remaining finish, and all proof marks are clearly legible. The wood grips are in great condition, as are the original holster and single magazine that come with the gun. The barrel has good rifling, and this gun functions flawlessly. This will be a great addition to your historical collection, and you will find it's sheer uniqueness to be fascinating. 
-Reasonable trades and negotiations considered.-

title: For Sale/Trade:  Accu Rest compound bow
postcontent:
I am selling an unusual and hard to find Accu Rest L/R compound bow. This bow is unusual in that it has a aluminum arrow rest assembly that is machined to accept the two arrow guide strips that form a slot to accept the fin adapters and arrow. The string of the bow travels down the center of the rest. Also attached to the rest is an arrow holding spring to keep the arrow in place at all times before the shot. The release is a dual caliper model with a pistol grip handle and trigger. When the bow is drawn the release, rest, string and arrow are all in equal motion. At release only the string and arrow move forward. The rest is mounted to the bow using an aluminum fixture equipped with five rollers. These rollers allow the rest to be drawn with no noise. The attachment fixture is also hinged to allow the bow to be placed in the stored/resting position.
